stream
BT
(Public Health Preparedness Guide) Tj
(Public health preparedness is the planning and coordination work that helps communities prevent, respond to, and recover from emergencies that affect health.) Tj
(Emergencies may include infectious disease outbreaks, extreme heat, floods, chemical releases, wildfire smoke, cyberattacks against hospitals, or interruptions to water and power systems.) Tj
(A preparedness program connects health departments, hospitals, emergency managers, schools, laboratories, community groups, and elected leaders before a crisis begins.) Tj
(Surveillance is one of the earliest preparedness functions. Health agencies watch emergency department visits, laboratory reports, wastewater signals, pharmacy trends, school absenteeism, and community complaints.) Tj
(Risk communication is another core capability. During an emergency, people need clear, timely, and trustworthy instructions.) Tj
(Messages should explain what is known, what is uncertain, what actions people should take, and where updates will appear.) Tj
(Medical surge planning prepares the health system for more patients than usual. Hospitals may need staffing plans, mutual aid agreements, supply caches, triage protocols, alternate care sites, and transportation coordination.) Tj
(Equity must be built into preparedness from the beginning. Emergencies often harm people most when they already face barriers such as unstable housing, disability, poverty, language isolation, chronic illness, or lack of transportation.) Tj
ET
endstream
