6 0 obj
<< /Length 3000 >>
stream
BT
(Public Health Preparedness Guide Continued) Tj
(Logistics determines whether plans become reality. Vaccines, masks, water, generators, medications, testing supplies, and shelter equipment must be stored, tracked, moved, and distributed.) Tj
(Distribution sites should be selected for accessibility, transit access, parking, crowd control, security, refrigeration needs, and communication capacity.) Tj
(Training and exercises help organizations practice before pressure is high. A tabletop exercise can test decision-making and communication, while a functional exercise can test staffing, systems, and handoffs.) Tj
(After-action reviews should identify what worked, what failed, who owns each fix, and when improvements will be completed.) Tj
(Preparedness also depends on legal and ethical clarity. Officials may need authority to issue isolation guidance, open emergency shelters, share data, request mutual aid, or prioritize scarce resources.) Tj
(Community resilience is broader than emergency response. Social connection, stable housing, food access, local clinics, reliable utilities, and trusted institutions all influence health outcomes during a disaster.) Tj
(Useful preparedness metrics include time to detect an outbreak, time to publish public guidance, residents reached in preferred languages, hospital bed availability, supply distribution speed, exercise completion, and closure of after-action items.) Tj
ET
endstream
